Data Analysis¶

Observations :¶

1. Skweness - From above we can see that Mean and the median is nearly same for the Cement, Water, Superplastic, Coarseagg, Fineagg and Strength. So we can say that dat for these attributes are approximately normally distributed. But in Slag, Ash and Age the mean is more than the median thus these are right skewed or positively skewed.¶
2. Outliers - From the above data distribution we can see that there are outliers in some columns.¶
a. Slag - Slag's maxinum of 359 is naerly 4 times the Stadndard Deviation of 86 over the mean 74. So 'Slag' has outliers¶
b. Water - Maximum value of 247 is just 3 times over the Standar Deviation of 21 above the mean of 181. So whikle its a bordeline case of whether water's data has outliers or not but we will do further analysis using boxplot to confirm¶
c. Superplastic - As the maximum value of 32.2 is greater than 3 standard deviation (5.97) over the mean - 6.2. Thus, superplastic has outliers.¶
d. Age - Mean + 3 Standard Deviation is 45.66 + 363.17 which is approximately equal to 236 but the maximum in column Age is 365. Thus, "Age" attribute has outliers¶
We will check using the box plots to what extent there are outliers¶

Fixing Outliers¶

As we have seen above outlier are present in the given dataset. There are multiple ways to deal with outliers but we mostly prefer either to drop the outliers or repalce it with median/mean.¶
Since there is not too much data given to begin with so dropping rows with outliers will only make the data set that much poorer. Therefore we will replace the outliers with median and this way we will not lose some important information.¶
I have also shown the number of outliers presence in each column in below code.¶

In [30]:
for col_name in dfconcrete_new.columns[:-1]:
    q1 = dfconcrete_new[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = dfconcrete_new[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    low = q1-1.75*iqr
    high = q3+1.75*iqr
    
    dfconcrete_new.loc[(dfconcrete_new[col_name] < low) | (dfconcrete_new[col_name] > high), col_name] = dfconcrete_new[col_name].median()

As can be seen the outliers which we had observed earlier have been replaced with the corresponding column's median. This replacement has thrown out 'new' outliers i.e. some data points which were not outliers to begin with, but when the data modification was done to replace the outliers with median, these data became new outliers. We will not replace these and let them be in the dataframe.¶

3. Feature Engineering techniques¶

3.1 Identify Opportunities (if any) to extract new features from existing features, drop a feature(if required)¶

Based on the correlation related observations as drwan from the heatmap and the subsequent countplots we can conclude that the following features have a significant impact on the outcome of the concrete's strength compared to other featues. These featues are whose variation we have observed vis-a-vis that of concrete's strength are:¶
1.'Water',¶
2. 'Cement'¶
3. 'Age',¶
4. 'Superplastic',¶
5. 'Coarse Aggregate' and¶
6. 'Fine aggregate'¶
We can draw additional functions / features that may impact the dependent i.e. the Strength of the concrete based on the cobination of these features driven by the analysis of the given data.¶

Add new functions:¶

1. Water to Cement ratio¶
2. Coarse Aggregate to Fine Aggregate ratio¶

Adding new features¶

2.1 Hypertuning of GradientBoostingRegressor using Grid Search CV' method¶

In [105]:

 'verbose': 0,
 'warm_start': False}
Here, we have opted for max_depth, n_estimators, max_features, and criterion hyperparameters to tune our model. The hyperparameters have the following definition.¶
max_depth: Maximum depth of a tree.¶
n_estimators: the number of trees which needs to be built before taking an average of predictions.¶
max_features: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.¶
criterion: The function to measure the quality of a split.¶
In the Gridsearch CV tuning process, one of the gold standards is to use cross-validation and taking the average result which provides reliable estimates of model performance. Here, we first perform a grid search of all combinations of hyperparameters. The parameters are added as a key-value combination inside a dictionary (param_grid). To try multiple values of hyperparameters we need to supply it as a list.¶
In order to start training, we need to initialize the GridSearchCV( ) method by supplying the estimator (gb_regressor), parameter grid (param_grid), a scoring function; here we are using negative mean absolute error as we want to minimize it. Then we set n_jobs = 4 to utilize 4 cores of the system (PC or cloud) for faster training. GBM training also supports GPU. Here, we are going to fit a 10-fold cross-validation model. Further, enabling refit=True refit the model with the best hyperparameters once tuning finished.¶
In [106]:
# Create a Gradient Boosted Regressor with specified criterion
gb_regressor = GradientBoostingRegressor(criterion = "mae")
In [107]:
# Create the parameter grid as part of Grid Search CV Hypertuning:
param_grid = {'max_depth' : [2, 4, 8, 10, 12],
              'n_estimators' : [100, 200, 300],
              'max_features' : ['auto', 'sqrt'],
              "criterion" : ["friedman_mse", "mse", "mae"]}
In [108]:
# Create a GridSearchCV object
grid_gb = GridSearchCV(
    estimator = gb_regressor,
    param_grid = param_grid,
    scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error',
    n_jobs = 4,
    cv = 10,
    refit = True,
    return_train_score = True)
